8E2B20B566C84B528C56A10A1FB4BC80.description: Know that there are numbers that are not rational, and approximate them by rational numbers.

8B6A71BBB3E94DB8AEFF9FA05EE0BEB9.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving the four operations with rational numbers. (Computations with rational numbers extend the rules for manipulating fractions to complex fractions.)

0E53D2CAA66044EDA72298780FBB5C6A.description: Convert a rational number to a decimal using long division; know that the decimal form of a rational number terminates in 0s or eventually repeats.

B48CA912DDBD410BBC18EBF402DBD3D2.description: Apply properties of operations as strategies to multiply and divide rational numbers.

A76B1744044545BF91821FA8A5568C32.description: Understand that integers can be divided, provided that the divisor is not zero, and every quotient of integers (with non-zero divisor) is a rational number. If p and q are integers then –(p/q) = (–p)/q = p/(–q). Interpret quotients of rational numbers by describing real-world contexts.

A093F86B196E490EA6A21E2669CF4614.description: Understand that multiplication is extended from fractions to rational numbers by requiring that operations continue to satisfy the properties of operations, particularly the distributive property, leading to products such as (–1)(–1) = 1 and the rules for multiplying signed numbers. Interpret products of rational numbers by describing real-world contexts.

82A08331E1174FB480CB6B0A0377F2B7.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division and of fractions to multiply and divide rational numbers.

4A0103B1211B4B26A4C2FC8588C13BB5.description: Apply properties of operations as strategies to add and subtract rational numbers.

269A9212633548BA83DF63F89D4F9992.description: Understand subtraction of rational numbers as adding the additive inverse, p – q = p + (–q). Show that the distance between two rational numbers on the number line is the absolute value of their difference, and apply this principle in real-world contexts.

07BF31451D18426AA8F522552E997D14.description: Understand p + q as the number located a distance |q| from p, in the positive or negative direction depending on whether q is positive or negative. Show that a number and its opposite have a sum of 0 (are additive inverses). Interpret sums of rational numbers by describing real-world contexts.

A90E71329B9041AE84EEB19C8688AEE4.description: Describe situations in which opposite quantities combine to make 0.

19F1281779F7457886887A8945E6E6C0.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of addition and subtraction to add and subtract rational numbers; represent addition and subtraction on a horizontal or vertical number line diagram.

5BEDE08424464AF3AD347EBDC9684022.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of operations with fractions to add, subtract, multiply, and divide rational numbers.

629F4D402E5141DE9E1AF8B70AF6773B.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems by graphing points in all four quadrants of the coordinate plane. Include use of coordinates and absolute value to find distances between points with the same first coordinate or the same second coordinate.

9C4F62DEF77B4B2AACA19FF85014B858.description: Distinguish comparisons of absolute value from statements about order.

E8044392B1DA42BBA4185BB98C9750AC.description: Understand the absolute value of a rational number as its distance from 0 on the number line; interpret absolute value as magnitude for a positive or negative quantity in a real-world situation.

968DEBEE27FC44F88A78D7C5A5CE772B.description: Write, interpret, and explain statements of order for rational numbers in real-world contexts.

20ACC432249F46D0B620E9423EE84B6B.description: Interpret statements of inequality as statements about the relative position of two numbers on a number line diagram.

6A7D4CFBB8EB49D4B199C6ECB2E0C6DD.description: Understand ordering and absolute value of rational numbers.

7F0D27DB4423421FAE2844B4385ACCF0.description: Find and position integers and other rational numbers on a horizontal or vertical number line diagram; find and position pairs of integers and other rational numbers on a coordinate plane.

6D23F47DD45E463AAABD80BE175B9EDC.description: Understand signs of numbers in ordered pairs as indicating locations in quadrants of the coordinate plane; recognize that when two ordered pairs differ only by signs, the locations of the points are related by reflections across one or both axes.

3D458E14C1A74512B969DD7B076E8555.description: Recognize opposite signs of numbers as indicating locations on opposite sides of 0 on the number line; recognize that the opposite of the opposite of a number is the number itself (e.g., –(–3) = 3, and that 0 is its own opposite).

2D71BCE7675447EB95C8926B581B2769.description: Understand a rational number as a point on the number line. Extend number line diagrams and coordinate axes familiar from previous grades to represent points on the line and in the plane with negative number coordinates.

66BE45F1786E4BFDBEBA088D2CF6FDBA.description: Understand that positive and negative numbers are used together to describe quantities having opposite directions or values (e.g., temperature above/below zero, elevation above/below sea level, debits/credits, positive/negative electric charge); use positive and negative numbers to represent quantities in real-world contexts, explaining the meaning of 0 in each situation.

81E92BB1F42A4E49BFF26F7520A109BB.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of numbers to the system of rational numbers.

DA9A8783B7E8450B83B5F31B17E5D27C.description: Find the greatest common factor of two whole numbers less than or equal to 100 and the least common multiple of two whole numbers less than or equal to 12. Use the distributive property to express a sum of two whole numbers 1–100 with a common factor as a multiple of a sum of two whole numbers with no common factor.

238ECA414D884A96BCD1B9BB06D54C78.description: Fluently add, subtract, multiply, and divide multi-digit decimals using the standard algorithm for each operation.

053C74020EF248E8B4882CC819EBA712.description: Fluently divide multi-digit numbers using the standard algorithm.

FD408537EEFA4E1FA93BB23008293040.description: Compute fluently with multi-digit numbers and find common factors and multiples.

3AA8CB73A2BB4815A1E6455E08C44A54.description: Interpret and compute quotients of fractions, and solve word problems involving division of fractions by fractions (e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem).

0A39E4AFC87645739122B955A571F874.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to divide fractions by fractions.

FB990AF21AE6486E8E95CA6882DFD963.description: Use proportional relationships to solve multistep ratio and percent problems.

8438EFB077C54E00A09284A8D0C855F4.description: Explain what a point (x, y) on the graph of a proportional relationship means in terms of the situation, with special attention to the points (0, 0) and (1, r) where r is the unit rate.

07991F10F07D4EC29EFCE9833CA741BF.description: Identify the constant of proportionality (unit rate) in tables, graphs, equations, diagrams, and verbal descriptions of proportional relationships.

39456C90D44A420CBB9D7E516B43DB1A.description: Decide whether two quantities are in a proportional relationship (e.g., by testing for equivalent ratios in a table or graphing on a coordinate plane and observing whether the graph is a straight line through the origin).

EAD5881B159146A6A03189E31184DF48.description: Recognize and represent proportional relationships between quantities.

66A13DAC2958485FAC503AB1F3156B44.description: Compute unit rates associated with ratios of fractions, including ratios of lengths, areas and other quantities measured in like or different units.

C2267BA316AC4D36BD3A3131D3AA9079.description: Analyze proportional relationships and use them to solve real-world and mathematical problems.

0CA8EBA90D3B4A429633C43893001966.description: Use ratio reasoning to convert measurement units; manipulate and transform units appropriately when multiplying or dividing quantities.

1ACF1DB8B4A24034AACAD36195633BDA.description: Find a percent of a quantity as a rate per 100 (e.g., 30% of a quantity means 30/100 times the quantity); solve problems involving finding the whole given a part and the percent.

64AFBB24677646AC892C7E59D0E07691.description: Solve unit rate problems including those involving unit pricing and constant speed.

46103BEC2B3A43C7A175A3647662ECF3.description: Make tables of equivalent ratios relating quantities with whole-number measurements, find missing values in the tables, and plot the pairs of values on the coordinate plane. Use tables to compare ratios.

759FF2FA4FF946368D43C20952B4B96E.description: Use ratio and rate reasoning to solve real-world and mathematical problems (e.g., by reasoning about tables of equivalent ratios, tape diagrams, double number line diagrams, or equations).

96C629070D9C45EFA7F6D9FF84DE5098.description: Understand the concept of a unit rate a/b associated with a ratio a:b with b ≠ 0 (b not equal to zero), and use rate language in the context of a ratio relationship.

128745B013E4408FBF9BBC0988F38167.description: Understand the concept of a ratio and use ratio language to describe a ratio relationship between two quantities.

5C7D31DDC6C741BFA697F195742D55B2.description: Understand ratio concepts and use ratio reasoning to solve problems.

C1BA233F46974021ACDF49297E4C7084.description: Solve real-world problems involving division of unit fractions by non-zero whole numbers and division of whole numbers by unit fractions (e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem).

98EB6CCEE225470CADF565FE4532B184.description: Interpret division of a whole number by a unit fraction, and compute such quotients.

F14C1D31E8DB4F94972C3506EF15FD24.description: Interpret division of a unit fraction by a non-zero whole number, and compute such quotients.

3A129F4AE8674F8E8713AECE18976943.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of division to divide unit fractions by whole numbers and whole numbers by unit fractions

88956E8A5E8E4D83867BF30E9CB3DBC8.description: Solve real world problems involving multiplication of fractions and mixed numbers (e.g., by using visual fraction models or equations to represent the problem).

ABD51F03341E45C38A36A7693D1F6A81.description: Explaining why multiplying a given number by a fraction greater than 1 results in a product greater than the given number (recognizing multiplication by whole numbers greater than 1 as a familiar case); explaining why multiplying a given number by a fraction less than 1 results in a product smaller than the given number; and relating the principle of fraction equivalence a/b = (n×a) / (n×b) to the effect of multiplying a/b by 1.

D8F2DEA6BBE142448FF9368E7C481BD7.description: Comparing the size of a product to the size of one factor on the basis of the size of the other factor, without performing the indicated multiplication.

DB8D3EEAB20142A5A9FF4FE13C51CC9E.description: Find the area of a rectangle with fractional side lengths by tiling it with unit squares of the appropriate unit fraction side lengths, and show that the area is the same as would be found by multiplying the side lengths. Multiply fractional side lengths to find areas of rectangles, and represent fraction products as rectangular areas.

59BCD26601E04D15A3AD91BBC64ECC4F.description: Interpret the product (a/b) × q as a parts of a partition of q into b equal parts; equivalently, as the result of a sequence of operations a × q ÷ b.

8985B5902B0542AB98DEDCFF7E5A8220.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication to multiply a fraction or whole number by a fraction.

71224822C2AB4F3C8BB56A0813957E3D.description: Interpret a fraction as division of the numerator by the denominator (a/b = a ÷ b). Solve word problems involving division of whole numbers leading to answers in the form of fractions or mixed numbers (e.g., by using visual fraction models or equations to represent the problem).

7AA86F5B12F64F28BCDCFCF2DFF068BA.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to multiply and divide fractions.

27F2500C53AA450D9966A071FEC6ECA3.description: Solve word problems involving addition and subtraction of fractions referring to the same whole, including cases of unlike denominators (e.g., by using visual fraction models or equations to represent the problem). Use benchmark fractions and number sense of fractions to estimate mentally and assess the reasonableness of answers.

DD20E497B22C471F9DA410BB3FB2834D.description: Add and subtract fractions with unlike denominators (including mixed numbers) by replacing given fractions with equivalent fractions in such a way as to produce an equivalent sum or difference of fractions with like denominators.

C76DFCCBCC8B462490CBDDDE4F6F28B7.description: Use equivalent fractions as a strategy to add and subtract fractions.

B76136FE8F6B4B78B7E3CECA4FFBE949.description: Compare two decimals to the hundredths place by reasoning about their size. Recognize that comparisons are valid only when two decimals refer to the same whole. Record the results of comparisons with the symbols >, =, or <, and justify the conclusions (e.g., by using a visual model).

1A7B7F5B6102464FA653AC51560B4100.description: Use decimal notation for fractions with denominators 10 or 100.

04AD194F1A15451591391809119335CD.description: Express a fraction with denominator 10 as an equivalent fraction with denominator 100, and use this technique to add two fractions with respective denominators 10 and 100.

656FD6376FDC4BCA987D59C7ED4E26F3.description: Understand decimal notation for fractions, and compare decimal fractions.

7B5191C5B7CE47B38FA8C55451768A22.description: Solve word problems involving multiplication of a fraction by a whole number (e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem).

9CB83CCFA779453CAE85F604490470D3.description: Understand a multiple of a/b as a multiple of 1/b, and use this understanding to multiply a fraction by a whole number.

3EEDAEDA2B7A432982CD021E10DCAA93.description: Understand a fraction a/b as a multiple of 1/b.

D5F2D066A3E946C9BD2CB0EC0DF8962F.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication to multiply a fraction by a whole number.

4685B4EB78AF4BD3AAB2985B869359CC.description: Solve word problems involving addition and subtraction of fractions referring to the same whole and having like denominators (e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem).

DAB9AD029D7341F5B2E7B16C044EDF88.description: Add and subtract mixed numbers with like denominators (e.g., by replacing each mixed number with an equivalent fraction, and/or by using properties of operations and the relationship between addition and subtraction).

E3772988E3F9403384AA477979C34798.description: Decompose a fraction into a sum of fractions with the same denominator in more than one way, recording each decomposition by an equation. Justify decompositions (e.g., by using a visual fraction model). Examples: 3/8 = 1/8 + 1/8 + 1/8; 3/8 = 1/8 + 2/8; 2 1/8 = 1 + 1 + 1/8 = 8/8 + 8/8 + 1/8.

4308EBE5FE4C49D5B0B47FB629F29DCA.description: Understand addition and subtraction of fractions as joining and separating parts referring to the same whole.

46DF3DAEA4FE4A70A7FAEE2D50BA4DC6.description: Understand a fraction a/b with a > 1 as a sum of fractions 1/b.

B49179CF57A4426B8CFF2E682EF70DF0.description: Build fractions from unit fractions by applying and extending previous understandings of operations on whole numbers.

0AABA65BAB2F4F36B58AAA3B80827287.description: Compare two fractions with different numerators and different denominators (e.g., by creating common denominators or numerators, or by comparing to a benchmark fraction such as ½). Recognize that comparisons are valid only when the two fractions refer to the same whole. Record the results of comparisons with symbols >, =, or <, and justify the conclusions (e.g., by using a visual fraction model).

CC73DF660D4A47AC9E02F328DE95A746.description: Explain why a fraction a/b is equivalent to a fraction (n × a)/(n × b) by using visual fraction models, with attention to how the number and size of the parts differ even though the two fractions themselves are the same size. Use this principle to recognize and generate equivalent fractions.

4C74D4B4C8C04822B87DE8A20A0A3422.description: Extend understanding of fraction equivalence and ordering.

927ABADA2F234137BA57C227D822C337.description: Compare two fractions with the same numerator or the same denominator by reasoning about their size. Recognize that comparisons are valid only when the two fractions refer to the same whole.

8C064AB8DC8E4EA19ABD72B57D43A55C.description: Express whole numbers as fractions, and recognize fractions that are equivalent to whole numbers. Examples: Express 3 in the form 3 = 3/1; recognize that 6/1 = 6; locate 4/4 and 1 at the same point of a number line diagram.

4DBC1AD7CA3C4F69AD30C9E500B6A3ED.description: Recognize and generate simple equivalent fractions (e.g., ½ = 2/4, 4/6 = 2/3). Explain why the fractions are equivalent (e.g., by using a visual fraction model).

C734B63C1B72426CAE2BDA743E991FB5.description: Understand two fractions as equivalent (equal) if they are the same size or the same point on a number line.

E2FCC81FB1254D00BFF58DD0F2D8F5A6.description: Explain equivalence of fractions in special cases, and compare fractions by reasoning about their size.

52A2DF9F27754B859D9521DF9BBC2AEF.description: Represent a fraction a/b on a number line diagram by marking off a lengths 1/b from 0. Recognize that the resulting interval has size a/b and that its endpoint locates the number a/b on the number line.

881053CCDC2143BFB72E206BA869D1C1.description: Represent a fraction 1/b on a number line diagram by defining the interval from 0 to 1 as the whole and partitioning it into b equal parts. Recognize that each part has size 1/b and that the endpoint of the part based at 0 locates the number 1/b on the number line.

414781ABBBE04E5BAE2967D199487CDD.description: Understand a fraction as a number on the number line; represent fractions on a number line diagram.

969047984E4D4B318AC4D5B97D564DB1.description: Understand a fraction 1/b as the quantity formed by 1 part when a whole is partitioned into b equal parts; understand a fraction a/b as the quantity formed by a parts of size 1/b.

71A5814355C841329F5CA60CB15284A2.description: Develop understanding of fractions as numbers.

F97989E509C94CCD89F416EAF5393872.description: Know the formulas for the volume of cones, cylinders, and spheres and use them to solve real-world and mathematical problems.

DB8607D5547E418AA809DFBBDBD7DD82.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving volume of cylinders, cones, and spheres.

54BBA206B4D94D64A5C4BF0177494596.description: Apply the Pythagorean Theorem to find the distance between two points in a coordinate system.

7A6FD1549482430BA5DE2CBA7EC9568B.description: Apply the Pythagorean Theorem to determine unknown side lengths in right triangles in real-world and mathematical problems in two and three dimensions.

1B9CD3E41F354A849B93C7520F4B2523.description: Explain a proof of the Pythagorean Theorem and its converse.

8E7676008F70431F8A608DBC2346B2F3.description: Understand and apply the Pythagorean Theorem.

5A74A10BE15D4731B86B42735CFD5736.description: Use informal arguments to establish facts about the angle sum and exterior angle of triangles, about the angles created when parallel lines are cut by a transversal, and the angle-angle criterion for similarity of triangles.

AA882E8CA4EC418F8B36021D890B1208.description: Understand that a two-dimensional figure is similar to another if the second can be obtained from the first by a sequence of rotations, reflections, translations, and dilations; given two similar two-dimensional figures, describe a sequence that exhibits the similarity between them.

598B71047BBE4FB098231C56E4622952.description: Describe the effect of dilations, translations, rotations, and reflections on two-dimensional figures using coordinates.

F2D865B9C57F4C5F8BC5858172C3FC14.description: Understand that a two-dimensional figure is congruent to another if the second can be obtained from the first by a sequence of rotations, reflections, and translations; given two congruent figures, describe a sequence that exhibits the congruence between them.

32BC3C5CE19944B9994080CFAE3B5EA1.description: Parallel lines are taken to parallel lines.

20B12F395D104199BD0A4245AAC0C338.description: Angles are taken to angles of the same measure.

F0A8E31C640144538615FABE8C64331E.description: Lines are taken to lines, and line segments to line segments of the same length.

F431B0E806A94A65BCA5663523CF90CE.description: Verify experimentally the properties of rotations, reflections, and translations:

F7A82BBE84EE4BD19310864E7454A4C0.description: Understand congruence and similarity using physical models, transparencies, or geometry software.

3A9799A6249945F4A487C7AE668F0711.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving area, volume and surface area of two- and three-dimensional objects composed of triangles, quadrilaterals, polygons, cubes, and right prisms.

29D61448D29F4780B12680E079FB493B.description: Use facts about supplementary, complementary, vertical, and adjacent angles in a multi-step problem to write and solve simple equations for an unknown angle in a figure.

C396372A89EC4E4DA4CB9F442BFA22E4.description: Know the formulas for the area and circumference of a circle and use them to solve problems; give an informal derivation of the relationship between the circumference and area of a circle.

2D73FD7B087F4DB8B3B5466BC98D9B39.description: Solve real-life and mathematical problems involving angle measure, area, surface area, and volume.

D90A98A0ED5F44B4A1562A99780B8A4E.description: Describe the two-dimensional figures that result from slicing three-dimensional figures, as in plane sections of right rectangular prisms and right rectangular pyramids.

D42402A037CF4710BD74C0C2C40BC35F.description: Draw (freehand, with ruler and protractor, and with technology) geometric shapes with given conditions. Focus on constructing triangles from three measures of angles or sides, noticing when the conditions determine a unique triangle, more than one triangle, or no triangle.

1E8BA789AE434D1C8D17D606DB38EA03.description: Solve problems involving scale drawings of geometric figures, including computing actual lengths and areas from a scale drawing and reproducing a scale drawing at a different scale.

0DCB0CCAD14F445FBA07665D49D25F56.description: Draw, construct, and describe geometrical figures and describe the relationships between them.

4787DB0D7A7C4D279F863BB184AE73EF.description: Represent three-dimensional figures using nets made up of rectangles and triangles, and use the nets to find the surface area of these figures. Apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

C0AF2F23C55640FC98275EE8526CA654.description: Draw polygons in the coordinate plane given coordinates for the vertices; use coordinates to find the length of a side joining points with the same first coordinate or the same second coordinate. Apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

E8E180CAFD394F7190396E2B5F542227.description: Find the volume of a right rectangular prism with fractional edge lengths by packing it with unit cubes of the appropriate unit fraction edge lengths, and show that the volume is the same as would be found by multiplying the edge lengths of the prism. Apply the formulas V = l w h and V = b h to find volumes of right rectangular prisms with fractional edge lengths in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

96BBBFB035F24EC8B5D03B0A5807815B.description: Find area of right triangles, other triangles, special quadrilaterals, and polygons by composing into rectangles or decomposing into triangles and other shapes; apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

5070484B363D45D7AC39CCBE7541CBA3.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving area, surface area, and volume.

258D624CC3BB48338F752472EB48C2D6.description: Classify two-dimensional figures in a hierarchy based on properties.

2F062FCABAF44250B4286B5B01E15668.description: Understand that attributes belonging to a category of two-dimensional figures also belong to all subcategories of that category.

64F1A898455F43CEACC79DD35CBF8B10.description: Classify two-dimensional figures into categories based on their properties.

3546672EBD244B87A00A9158A477278C.description: Represent real world and mathematical problems by graphing points in the first quadrant of the coordinate plane, and interpret coordinate values of points in the context of the situation.

680328D091054B01901DF844EB2F4E65.description: Use a pair of perpendicular number lines, called axes, to define a coordinate system, with the intersection of the lines (the origin) arranged to coincide with the 0 on each line and a given point in the plane located by using an ordered pair of numbers, called its coordinates. Understand that the first number indicates how far to travel from the origin in the direction of one axis, and the second number indicates how far to travel in the direction of the second axis, with the convention that the names of the two axes and the coordinates correspond (e.g., x-axis and x-coordinate, y-axis and y-coordinate).

F5AE0B5A02CC47D79E103223D4CF408A.description: Graph points on the coordinate plane to solve real-world and mathematical problems.

EA826B7C02A8424896A167DB7F835EB4.description: Recognize a line of symmetry for a two-dimensional figure as a line across the figure such that the figure can be folded along the line into matching parts. Identify line-symmetric figures and draw lines of symmetry.

ADC57DF46D04436085C99ABE7B945FAA.description: Classify two-dimensional figures based on the presence or absence of parallel or perpendicular lines, or the presence or absence of angles of a specified size. Recognize right triangles as a category, and identify right triangles.

D38FD84DD3C5451596CA41D61D61ED0B.description: Draw points, lines, line segments, rays, angles (right, acute, obtuse), and perpendicular and parallel lines. Identify these in two-dimensional figures.

7F4BF99B847B4AC1AD04D317FB8FEC54.description: Draw and identify lines and angles, and classify shapes by properties of their lines and angles.

6BA6A4BF986B41B0BFBAB8F76FF59625.description: Partition shapes into parts with equal areas. Express the area of each part as a unit fraction of the whole.

727078385AB84FE6A642EDFAEC74E14B.description: Understand that shapes in different categories (e.g., rhombuses, rectangles, and others) may share attributes (e.g., having four sides), and that the shared attributes can define a larger category (e.g., quadrilaterals). Recognize rhombuses, rectangles, and squares as examples of quadrilaterals, and draw examples of quadrilaterals that do not belong to any of these subcategories.

98DFFAA170DB4E68A6F6FA134B70A5C9.description: Partition circles and rectangles into two, three, or four equal shares, describe the shares using the words halves, thirds, half of, a third of, etc., and describe the whole as two halves, three thirds, four fourths. Recognize that equal shares of identical wholes need not have the same shape.

138607554F2E482DAF7689CAE96AF03A.description: Partition a rectangle into rows and columns of same-size squares and count to find the total number of them.

D1304C36DFAA4773B06ED864779A41CA.description: Recognize and draw shapes having specified attributes, such as a given number of angles or a given number of equal faces. Identify triangles, quadrilaterals, pentagons, hexagons, and cubes. Sizes are compared directly or visually, not compared by measuring.

A468726E2B3A4062B5D4D3874FEFD103.description: Partition circles and rectangles into two and four equal shares, describe the shares using the words halves, fourths, and quarters, and use the phrases half of, fourth of, and quarter of. Describe the whole as two of or four of the shares. Understand for these examples that decomposing into more equal shares creates smaller shares.

0D234C82CD594522841A1655B324225F.description: Compose two-dimensional shapes (rectangles, squares, trapezoids, triangles, half-circles, and quarter-circles) or three-dimensional shapes (cubes, right rectangular prisms, right circular cones, and right circular cylinders) to create a composite shape, and compose new shapes from the composite shape. Students do not need to learn formal names such as "right rectangular prism."

24D40755BAE540638723AEA49FFAC4E3.description: Distinguish between defining attributes (e.g., triangles are closed and three-sided) versus non-defining attributes (e.g., color, orientation, overall size); build and draw shapes to possess defining attributes.

BD29967694804CE38D6FAFBB1933E711.description: Reason with shapes and their attributes.

D38B1274BF584237973692B80DB5C6A0.description: Compose simple shapes to form larger shapes.

To add 2 + 6 + 4, the second two numbers can be added to make a ten, so 2 + 6 + 4 = 2 + 10 = 12 (associative property of addition). Students need not use formal terms for these properties.

7B9A7495E57D452DA1DBAA31C66D5E13.description: Understand and apply properties and the relationship between addition and subtraction.

55505DE621174EA8A1789DF01E7EF68F.description: Use addition and subtraction within 100 to solve one- and two-step word problems involving situations of adding to, taking from, putting together, taking apart, and comparing, with unknowns in all positions (e.g., by using drawings and equations with a symbol for the unknown number to represent the problem).

D5AF55C8376C49EB9D496BD3018B754F.description: Solve word problems that call for addition of three whole numbers whose sum is less than or equal to 20 (e.g., by using objects, drawings, and equations with a symbol for the unknown number to represent the problem).

7557825AE3CF4B1FBC4D20E9A39345D7.description: Use addition and subtraction within 20 to solve word problems involving situations of adding to, taking from, putting together, taking apart, and comparing, with unknowns in all positions (e.g., by using objects, drawings, and equations with a symbol for the unknown number to represent the problem).

CF8A5811516B411EB23190B25B3ED046.description: Represent and solve problems involving addition and subtraction.

28D846AF8BA74DA7854ADDCB2DFAFF5C.description: For any number from 1 to 9, find the number that makes 10 when added to the given number (e.g., by using objects or drawings), and record the answer with a drawing or equation.

F0D9FC9933634C909AE2338E8AD2FFB5.description: Decompose numbers less than or equal to 10 into pairs in more than one way (e.g., by using objects or drawings), and record each decomposition by a drawing or equation (e.g., 5 = 2 + 3 and 5 = 4 + 1).

4D92651D75644B17AFE8A17DE85CA13F.description: Solve addition and subtraction word problems, and add and subtract within 10 (e.g., by using objects or drawings to represent the problem).

CF8312A3608A48FC8A4CC4FCC9FEE410.description: Represent addition and subtraction with objects, fingers, mental images, drawings, sounds (e.g., claps), and acting out situations, verbal explanations, expressions, or equations. Drawings need not show details, but should show the mathematics in the problem.

05B87A306D3F45B4BE018EA1C831AEDF.description: Understand addition as putting together and adding to, and understand subtraction as taking apart and taking from.

073F427286EE42439CC1EA53D0770197.description: Compare two numbers between 1 and 10 presented as written numerals.

B603A6DF2EFE48EE8F226B7F0B7009E2.description: Identify whether the number of objects in one group is greater than, less than, or equal to the number of objects in another group (e.g., by using matching and counting strategies). Include groups with up to ten objects.

EAFCE1902D11483F899E333EB16E0A5B.description: Count to answer "how many?" questions about as many as 20 things arranged in a line, a rectangular array, or a circle, or as many as 10 things in a scattered configuration; given a number from 1–20, count out that many objects.

C25D29D6B7BF45E2A94A470443C0849C.description: Understand that each successive number name refers to a quantity that is one larger.

8F18EAEB483B4FA9A95DB8B8CEEF2931.description: Understand that the last number name said tells the number of objects counted. The number of objects is the same regardless of their arrangement or the order in which they were counted.

C4E69815538A4B5292F749423F44C575.description: When counting objects, say the number names in the standard order, pairing each object with one and only one number name and each number name with one and only one object.

2FDDB267ACC34926A55D8B0D4CFFBFF2.description: Understand the relationship between numbers and quantities; connect counting to cardinality.

CDA7651BB00548D9B02CA8A532B1F14B.description: Count to tell the number of objects.

2F88D7552BFF4440B476BC7C1170A0A8.description: Write numbers from 0 to 20. Represent a number of objects with a written numeral 0-20 (with 0 representing a count of no objects).

59CEE5A2062B481BA91EE3722EDFABA8.description: Count forward beginning from a given number within the known sequence (instead of having to begin at 1).

3AC29A89A9504EDB9F5A59533D1B9B2D.description: Count to 100 by ones and by tens.

0DD7BCCC33D8497FBFE139A2E1E37D11.description: Know number names and the count sequence.
